                    4082   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    4083   ; *                          CHECK THE STATUS OF FLAGS IN AN EVENT FLAG GROUP
                    4084   ; *
                    4085   ; * Description: This function is called to check the status of a combination of bits to be set or cleared
                    4086   ; *              in an event flag group.  Your application can check for ANY bit to be set/cleared or ALL
                    4087   ; *              bits to be set/cleared.
                    4088   ; *
                    4089   ; *              This call does not block if the desired flags are not present.
                    4090   ; *
                    4091   ; * Arguments  : pgrp          is a pointer to the desired event flag group.
                    4092   ; *
                    4093   ; *              flags         Is a bit pattern indicating which bit(s) (i.e. flags) you wish to check.
                    4094   ; *                            The bits you want are specified by setting the corresponding bits in
                    4095   ; *                            'flags'.  e.g. if your application wants to wait for bits 0 and 1 then
                    4096   ; *                            'flags' would contain 0x03.
                    4097   ; *
                    4098   ; *              wait_type     specifies whether you want ALL bits to be set/cleared or ANY of the bits
                    4099   ; *                            to be set/cleared.
                    4100   ; *                            You can specify the following argument:
                    4101   ; *
                    4102   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_CLR_ALL   You will check ALL bits in 'flags' to be clear (0)
                    4103   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_CLR_ANY   You will check ANY bit  in 'flags' to be clear (0)
                    4104   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_SET_ALL   You will check ALL bits in 'flags' to be set   (1)
                    4105   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_SET_ANY   You will check ANY bit  in 'flags' to be set   (1)
                    4106   ; *
                    4107   ; *                            NOTE: Add OS_FLAG_CONSUME if you want the event flag to be 'consumed' by
                    4108   ; *                                  the call.  Example, to wait for any flag in a group AND then clear
                    4109   ; *                                  the flags that are present, set 'wait_type' to:
                    4110   ; *
                    4111   ; *                                  OS_FLAG_WAIT_SET_ANY + OS_FLAG_CONSUME
                    4112   ; *
                    4113   ; *              perr          is a pointer to an error code and can be:
                    4114   ; *                            OS_ERR_NONE               No error
                    4115   ; *                            OS_ERR_EVENT_TYPE         You are not pointing to an event flag group
                    4116   ; *                            OS_ERR_FLAG_WAIT_TYPE     You didn't specify a proper 'wait_type' argument.
                    4117   ; *                            OS_ERR_FLAG_INVALID_PGRP  You passed a NULL pointer instead of the event flag
                    4118   ; *                                                      group handle.
                    4119   ; *                            OS_ERR_FLAG_NOT_RDY       The desired flags you are waiting for are not
                    4120   ; *                                                      available.
                    4121   ; *
                    4122   ; * Returns    : The flags in the event flag group that made the task ready or, 0 if a timeout or an error
                    4123   ; *              occurred.
                    4124   ; *
                    4125   ; * Called from: Task or ISR
                    4126   ; *
                    4127   ; * Note(s)    : 1) IMPORTANT, the behavior of this function has changed from PREVIOUS versions.  The
                    4128   ; *                 function NOW returns the flags that were ready INSTEAD of the current state of the
                    4129   ; *                 event flags.
                    4130   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    4131   ; */
