                    4909   ; /*
                    4910   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    4911   ; *                                     WAIT ON AN EVENT FLAG GROUP
                    4912   ; *
                    4913   ; * Description: This function is called to wait for a combination of bits to be set in an event flag
                    4914   ; *              group.  Your application can wait for ANY bit to be set or ALL bits to be set.
                    4915   ; *
                    4916   ; * Arguments  : pgrp          is a pointer to the desired event flag group.
                    4917   ; *
                    4918   ; *              flags         Is a bit pattern indicating which bit(s) (i.e. flags) you wish to wait for.
                    4919   ; *                            The bits you want are specified by setting the corresponding bits in
                    4920   ; *                            'flags'.  e.g. if your application wants to wait for bits 0 and 1 then
                    4921   ; *                            'flags' would contain 0x03.
                    4922   ; *
                    4923   ; *              wait_type     specifies whether you want ALL bits to be set or ANY of the bits to be set.
                    4924   ; *                            You can specify the following argument:
                    4925   ; *
                    4926   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_CLR_ALL   You will wait for ALL bits in 'mask' to be clear (0)
                    4927   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_SET_ALL   You will wait for ALL bits in 'mask' to be set   (1)
                    4928   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_CLR_ANY   You will wait for ANY bit  in 'mask' to be clear (0)
                    4929   ; *                            OS_FLAG_WAIT_SET_ANY   You will wait for ANY bit  in 'mask' to be set   (1)
                    4930   ; *
                    4931   ; *                            NOTE: Add OS_FLAG_CONSUME if you want the event flag to be 'consumed' by
                    4932   ; *                                  the call.  Example, to wait for any flag in a group AND then clear
                    4933   ; *                                  the flags that are present, set 'wait_type' to:
                    4934   ; *
                    4935   ; *                                  OS_FLAG_WAIT_SET_ANY + OS_FLAG_CONSUME
                    4936   ; *
                    4937   ; *              timeout       is an optional timeout (in clock ticks) that your task will wait for the
                    4938   ; *                            desired bit combination.  If you specify 0, however, your task will wait
                    4939   ; *                            forever at the specified event flag group or, until a message arrives.
                    4940   ; *
                    4941   ; *              perr          is a pointer to an error code and can be:
                    4942   ; *                            OS_ERR_NONE               The desired bits have been set within the specified
                    4943   ; *                                                      'timeout'.
                    4944   ; *                            OS_ERR_PEND_ISR           If you tried to PEND from an ISR
                    4945   ; *                            OS_ERR_FLAG_INVALID_PGRP  If 'pgrp' is a NULL pointer.
                    4946   ; *                            OS_ERR_EVENT_TYPE         You are not pointing to an event flag group
                    4947   ; *                            OS_ERR_TIMEOUT            The bit(s) have not been set in the specified
                    4948   ; *                                                      'timeout'.
                    4949   ; *                            OS_ERR_PEND_ABORT         The wait on the flag was aborted.
                    4950   ; *                            OS_ERR_FLAG_WAIT_TYPE     You didn't specify a proper 'wait_type' argument.
                    4951   ; *
                    4952   ; * Returns    : The flags in the event flag group that made the task ready or, 0 if a timeout or an error
                    4953   ; *              occurred.
                    4954   ; *
                    4955   ; * Called from: Task ONLY
                    4956   ; *
                    4957   ; * Note(s)    : 1) IMPORTANT, the behavior of this function has changed from PREVIOUS versions.  The
                    4958   ; *                 function NOW returns the flags that were ready INSTEAD of the current state of the
                    4959   ; *                 event flags.
                    4960   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    4961   ; */
