                    8061   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    8062   ; *                                  ACCEPT MUTUAL EXCLUSION SEMAPHORE
                    8063   ; *
                    8064   ; * Description: This  function checks the mutual exclusion semaphore to see if a resource is available.
                    8065   ; *              Unlike OSMutexPend(), OSMutexAccept() does not suspend the calling task if the resource is
                    8066   ; *              not available or the event did not occur.
                    8067   ; *
                    8068   ; * Arguments  : pevent     is a pointer to the event control block
                    8069   ; *
                    8070   ; *              perr       is a pointer to an error code which will be returned to your application:
                    8071   ; *                            OS_ERR_NONE         if the call was successful.
                    8072   ; *                            OS_ERR_EVENT_TYPE   if 'pevent' is not a pointer to a mutex
                    8073   ; *                            OS_ERR_PEVENT_NULL  'pevent' is a NULL pointer
                    8074   ; *                            OS_ERR_PEND_ISR     if you called this function from an ISR
                    8075   ; *                            OS_ERR_PCP_LOWER    If the priority of the task that owns the Mutex is
                    8076   ; *                                                HIGHER (i.e. a lower number) than the PCP.  This error
                    8077   ; *                                                indicates that you did not set the PCP higher (lower
                    8078   ; *                                                number) than ALL the tasks that compete for the Mutex.
                    8079   ; *                                                Unfortunately, this is something that could not be
                    8080   ; *                                                detected when the Mutex is created because we don't know
                    8081   ; *                                                what tasks will be using the Mutex.
                    8082   ; *
                    8083   ; * Returns    : == OS_TRUE    if the resource is available, the mutual exclusion semaphore is acquired
                    8084   ; *              == OS_FALSE   a) if the resource is not available
                    8085   ; *                            b) you didn't pass a pointer to a mutual exclusion semaphore
                    8086   ; *                            c) you called this function from an ISR
                    8087   ; *
                    8088   ; * Warning(s) : This function CANNOT be called from an ISR because mutual exclusion semaphores are
                    8089   ; *              intended to be used by tasks only.
                    8090   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    8091   ; */
