                    8389   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    8390   ; *                                           DELETE A MUTEX
                    8391   ; *
                    8392   ; * Description: This function deletes a mutual exclusion semaphore and readies all tasks pending on the it.
                    8393   ; *
                    8394   ; * Arguments  : pevent        is a pointer to the event control block associated with the desired mutex.
                    8395   ; *
                    8396   ; *              opt           determines delete options as follows:
                    8397   ; *                            opt == OS_DEL_NO_PEND   Delete mutex ONLY if no task pending
                    8398   ; *                            opt == OS_DEL_ALWAYS    Deletes the mutex even if tasks are waiting.
                    8399   ; *                                                    In this case, all the tasks pending will be readied.
                    8400   ; *
                    8401   ; *              perr          is a pointer to an error code that can contain one of the following values:
                    8402   ; *                            OS_ERR_NONE             The call was successful and the mutex was deleted
                    8403   ; *                            OS_ERR_DEL_ISR          If you attempted to delete the MUTEX from an ISR
                    8404   ; *                            OS_ERR_INVALID_OPT      An invalid option was specified
                    8405   ; *                            OS_ERR_TASK_WAITING     One or more tasks were waiting on the mutex
                    8406   ; *                            OS_ERR_EVENT_TYPE       If you didn't pass a pointer to a mutex
                    8407   ; *                            OS_ERR_PEVENT_NULL      If 'pevent' is a NULL pointer.
                    8408   ; *
                    8409   ; * Returns    : pevent        upon error
                    8410   ; *              (OS_EVENT *)0 if the mutex was successfully deleted.
                    8411   ; *
                    8412   ; * Note(s)    : 1) This function must be used with care.  Tasks that would normally expect the presence of
                    8413   ; *                 the mutex MUST check the return code of OSMutexPend().
                    8414   ; *
                    8415   ; *              2) This call can potentially disable interrupts for a long time.  The interrupt disable
                    8416   ; *                 time is directly proportional to the number of tasks waiting on the mutex.
                    8417   ; *
                    8418   ; *              3) Because ALL tasks pending on the mutex will be readied, you MUST be careful because the
                    8419   ; *                 resource(s) will no longer be guarded by the mutex.
                    8420   ; *
                    8421   ; *              4) IMPORTANT: In the 'OS_DEL_ALWAYS' case, we assume that the owner of the Mutex (if there
                    8422   ; *                            is one) is ready-to-run and is thus NOT pending on another kernel object or
                    8423   ; *                            has delayed itself.  In other words, if a task owns the mutex being deleted,
                    8424   ; *                            that task will be made ready-to-run at its original priority.
                    8425   ; *********************************************************************************************************
                    8426   ; */
